props.name: name
props.documentation: name / id of the buttons (for tracking)

props.name: title
props.documentation:
text that appears while hovering over the button,
enter null, false or '' for no hover text

props.name: icon
props.documentation:
svg icon object associated with the button
can be linked to Plotly.Icons to use the default plotly icons

props.name: gravity
props.documentation: icon positioning

props.name: click
props.documentation:
click handler associated with the button, a function of
'gd' (the main graph object) and
'ev' (the event object)

props.name: attr
props.documentation:
attribute associated with button,
use this with 'val' to keep track of the state

props.name: val
props.documentation: initial 'attr' value, can be a function of gd

props.name: toggle
props.documentation: is the button a toggle button?

name: TransformStyle
documentation:
These interfaces are based on attribute descriptions in
https://github.com/plotly/plotly.js/tree/9d6144304308fc3007f0facf2535d38ea3e9b26c/src/transforms

name: PlotMarker
documentation:
Any combination of "x", "y", "z", "text", "name" joined with a "+" OR "all" or "none" or "skip".
examples: "x", "y", "x+y", "x+y+z", "all"
default: "all"

props.name: family
props.documentation:
HTML font family - the typeface that will be applied by the web browser.
The web browser will only be able to apply a font if it is available on the system
which it operates. Provide multiple font families, separated by commas, to indicate
the preference in which to apply fonts if they aren't available on the system.
The plotly service (at https://plot.ly or on-premise) generates images on a server,
where only a select number of fonts are installed and supported.
These include *Arial*, *Balto*, *Courier New*, *Droid Sans*, *Droid Serif*,
*Droid Sans Mono*, *Gravitas One*, *Old Standard TT*, *Open Sans*, *Overpass*,
*PT Sans Narrow*, *Raleway*, *Times New Roman*.

props.name: toImageButtonOptions
props.documentation: override the defaults for the toImageButton

props.name: staticPlot
props.documentation: no interactivity, for export or image generation

props.name: editable
props.documentation: we can edit titles, move annotations, etc

props.name: autosizable
props.documentation: DO autosize once regardless of layout.autosize (use default width or height values otherwise)

props.name: queueLength
props.documentation: set the length of the undo/redo queue

props.name: fillFrame
props.documentation: if we DO autosize, do we fill the container or the screen?

props.name: frameMargins
props.documentation: if we DO autosize, set the frame margins in percents of plot size

props.name: scrollZoom
props.documentation: mousewheel or two-finger scroll zooms the plot

props.name: doubleClick
props.documentation: double click interaction (false, 'reset', 'autosize' or 'reset+autosize')

props.name: showTips
props.documentation: new users see some hints about interactivity

props.name: showAxisDragHandles
props.documentation: enable axis pan/zoom drag handles

props.name: showAxisRangeEntryBoxes
props.documentation: enable direct range entry at the pan/zoom drag points (drag handles must be enabled above)

props.name: showLink
props.documentation: link to open this plot in plotly

props.name: sendData
props.documentation: if we show a link, does it contain data or just link to a plotly file?

props.name: linkText
props.documentation: text appearing in the sendData link

props.name: showSources
props.documentation: false or function adding source(s) to linkText <text>

props.name: displayModeBar
props.documentation: display the mode bar (true, false, or 'hover')

props.name: modeBarButtonsToRemove
props.documentation: remove mode bar button by name (see ./components/modebar/buttons.js for the list of names)

props.name: modeBarButtonsToAdd
props.documentation: add mode bar button using config objects (see ./components/modebar/buttons.js for list of arguments)

props.name: modeBarButtons
props.documentation:
fully custom mode bar buttons as nested array, where the outer
arrays represents button groups, and the inner arrays have
buttons config objects or names of default buttons
(see ./components/modebar/buttons.js for more info)

props.name: displaylogo
props.documentation: add the plotly logo on the end of the mode bar

props.name: plotGlPixelRatio
props.documentation: increase the pixel ratio for Gl plot images

props.name: setBackground
props.documentation:
function to add the background color to a different container
or 'opaque' to ensure there's white behind it

props.name: topojsonURL
props.documentation: URL to topojson files used in geo charts

props.name: mapboxAccessToken
props.documentation:
Mapbox access token (required to plot mapbox trace types)
If using an Mapbox Atlas server, set this option to '',
so that plotly.js won't attempt to authenticate to the public Mapbox server.

props.name: logging
props.documentation:
Turn all console logging on or off (errors will be thrown)
This should ONLY be set via Plotly.setPlotConfig

props.name: globalTransforms
props.documentation: Set global transform to be applied to all traces with no specification needed

props.name: locale
props.documentation: Which localization should we use? Should be a string like 'en' or 'en-US'

props.name: responsive
props.documentation: Make the chart responsive to window size

props.name: bgcolor
props.documentation: Sets the background color of all hover labels on graph.

props.name: bordercolor
props.documentation: Sets the border color of all hover labels on graph.

props.name: font
props.documentation: Sets the default hover label font used by all traces on the graph.

props.name: align
props.documentation: Sets the horizontal alignment of the text content within hover label box.

props.name: namelength
props.documentation:
Sets the default length (in number of characters) (default 15) of the trace name
in the hover labels for all traces.
-1 shows the whole name regardless of length.

props.name: visible
props.documentation: Determines whether or not this annotation is visible.

props.name: text
props.documentation:
Sets the text associated with this annotation. Plotly uses a subset of HTML tags to do things like newline (
), bold (), italics (), hyperlinks (). Tags , , are also supported.

props.name: textangle
props.documentation: Sets the angle at which the `text` is drawn with respect to the horizontal.

props.name: width
props.documentation:
Sets an explicit width for the text box. null (default) lets the text set the box width. Wider text will be clipped. There is no automatic wrapping; use
to start a new line.

props.name: height
props.documentation:
Sets an explicit height for the text box. null (default) lets the
text set the box height. Taller text will be clipped.

props.name: opacity
props.documentation: Sets the opacity of the annotation (text + arrow).

props.name: align
props.documentation:
Sets the horizontal alignment of the `text` within the box. Has an effect only if `text` spans more two or more lines (i.e. `text` contains one or more
HTML tags) or if an explicit width is set to override the text width.

props.name: valign
props.documentation:
Sets the vertical alignment of the `text` within the box.
Has an effect only if an explicit height is set to override the text height.

props.name: borderpad
props.documentation: Sets the padding (in px) between the `text` and the enclosing border.

props.name: borderwidth
props.documentation: Sets the width (in px) of the border enclosing the annotation `text`.

props.name: showarrow
props.documentation:
Determines whether or not the annotation is drawn with an arrow.
If *true*, `text` is placed near the arrow's tail.
If *false*, `text` lines up with the `x` and `y` provided.

props.name: arrowcolor
props.documentation: Sets the color of the annotation arrow.

props.name: arrowhead
props.documentation: Sets the end annotation arrow head style.

props.name: startarrowhead
props.documentation: Sets the start annotation arrow head style.

props.name: arrowside
props.documentation: Sets the annotation arrow head position.

props.name: arrowsize
props.documentation:
Sets the size of the end annotation arrow head, relative to `arrowwidth`.
A value of 1 (default) gives a head about 3x as wide as the line.

props.name: startarrowsize
props.documentation:
Sets the size of the start annotation arrow head, relative to `arrowwidth`.
A value of 1 (default) gives a head about 3x as wide as the line.

props.name: arrowwidth
props.documentation: Sets the width (in px) of annotation arrow line.

props.name: standoff
props.documentation:
Sets a distance, in pixels, to move the end arrowhead away from the
position it is pointing at, for example to point at the edge of
a marker independent of zoom. Note that this shortens the arrow
from the `ax` / `ay` vector, in contrast to `xshift` / `yshift`
which moves everything by this amount.

props.name: startstandoff
props.documentation:
Sets a distance, in pixels, to move the start arrowhead away from the
position it is pointing at, for example to point at the edge of
a marker independent of zoom. Note that this shortens the arrow
from the `ax` / `ay` vector, in contrast to `xshift` / `yshift`
which moves everything by this amount.

props.name: ax
props.documentation:
Sets the x component of the arrow tail about the arrow head.
If `axref` is `pixel`, a positive (negative)
component corresponds to an arrow pointing
from right to left (left to right).
If `axref` is an axis, this is an absolute value on that axis,
like `x`, NOT a relative value.

props.name: ay
props.documentation:
Sets the y component of the arrow tail about the arrow head.
If `ayref` is `pixel`, a positive (negative)
component corresponds to an arrow pointing
from bottom to top (top to bottom).
If `ayref` is an axis, this is an absolute value on that axis,
like `y`, NOT a relative value.

props.name: axref
props.documentation:
Indicates in what terms the tail of the annotation (ax,ay)
is specified. If `pixel`, `ax` is a relative offset in pixels
from `x`. If set to an x axis id (e.g. *x* or *x2*), `ax` is
specified in the same terms as that axis. This is useful
for trendline annotations which should continue to indicate
the correct trend when zoomed.

props.name: ayref
props.documentation:
Indicates in what terms the tail of the annotation (ax,ay)
is specified. If `pixel`, `ay` is a relative offset in pixels
from `y`. If set to a y axis id (e.g. *y* or *y2*), `ay` is
specified in the same terms as that axis. This is useful
for trendline annotations which should continue to indicate
the correct trend when zoomed.

props.name: xref
props.documentation:
Sets the annotation's x coordinate axis.
If set to an x axis id (e.g. *x* or *x2*), the `x` position refers to an x coordinate
If set to *paper*, the `x` position refers to the distance from
the left side of the plotting area in normalized coordinates
where 0 (1) corresponds to the left (right) side.

props.name: x
props.documentation:
Sets the annotation's x position.
If the axis `type` is *log*, then you must take the log of your desired range.
If the axis `type` is *date*, it should be date strings, like date data,
though Date objects and unix milliseconds will be accepted and converted to strings.
If the axis `type` is *category*, it should be numbers, using the scale where each
category is assigned a serial number from zero in the order it appears.

props.name: xanchor
props.documentation:
Sets the text box's horizontal position anchor
This anchor binds the `x` position to the *left*, *center* or *right* of the annotation.
For example, if `x` is set to 1, `xref` to *paper* and `xanchor` to *right* then the
right-most portion of the annotation lines up with the right-most edge of the plotting area.
If *auto*, the anchor is equivalent to *center* for data-referenced annotations or if there
is an arrow, whereas for paper-referenced with no arrow, the anchor picked corresponds to the closest side.

props.name: xshift
props.documentation:
Shifts the position of the whole annotation and arrow to the
right (positive) or left (negative) by this many pixels.

props.name: yref
props.documentation:
Sets the annotation's y coordinate axis.
If set to an y axis id (e.g. *y* or *y2*), the `y` position refers to an y coordinate
If set to *paper*, the `y` position refers to the distance from
the bottom of the plotting area in normalized coordinates
where 0 (1) corresponds to the bottom (top).

props.name: y
props.documentation:
Sets the annotation's y position.
If the axis `type` is *log*, then you must take the log of your desired range.
If the axis `type` is *date*, it should be date strings, like date data,
though Date objects and unix milliseconds will be accepted and converted to strings.
If the axis `type` is *category*, it should be numbers, using the scale where each
category is assigned a serial number from zero in the order it appears.

props.name: yanchor
props.documentation:
Sets the text box's vertical position anchor
This anchor binds the `y` position to the *top*, *middle* or *bottom* of the annotation.
For example, if `y` is set to 1, `yref` to *paper* and `yanchor` to *top* then the
top-most portion of the annotation lines up with the top-most edge of the plotting area.
If *auto*, the anchor is equivalent to *middle* for data-referenced annotations or if
there is an arrow, whereas for paper-referenced with no arrow, the anchor picked
corresponds to the closest side.

props.name: yshift
props.documentation:
Shifts the position of the whole annotation and arrow up
(positive) or down (negative) by this many pixels.

props.name: clicktoshow
props.documentation:
Makes this annotation respond to clicks on the plot.
If you click a data point that exactly matches the `x` and `y` values of this annotation,
and it is hidden (visible: false), it will appear. In *onoff* mode, you must click the same
point again to make it disappear, so if you click multiple points, you can show multiple
annotations. In *onout* mode, a click anywhere else in the plot (on another data point or not)
will hide this annotation. If you need to show/hide this annotation in response to different
`x` or `y` values, you can set `xclick` and/or `yclick`. This is useful for example to label
the side of a bar. To label markers though, `standoff` is preferred over `xclick` and `yclick`.

props.name: xclick
props.documentation:
Toggle this annotation when clicking a data point whose `x` value
is `xclick` rather than the annotation's `x` value.

props.name: yclick
props.documentation:
Toggle this annotation when clicking a data point whose `y` value
is `yclick` rather than the annotation's `y` value.

props.name: hovertext
props.documentation:
Sets text to appear when hovering over this annotation.
If omitted or blank, no hover label will appear.

props.name: captureevents
props.documentation:
Determines whether the annotation text box captures mouse move and click events,
or allows those events to pass through to data points in the plot that may be
behind the annotation. By default `captureevents` is *false* unless `hovertext`
is provided. If you use the event `plotly_clickannotation` without `hovertext`
you must explicitly enable `captureevents`.

props.name: group
props.documentation:
An identifier that specifies the group to which the frame belongs,
used by animate to select a subset of frames.

props.name: name
props.documentation: A label by which to identify the frame

props.name: traces
props.documentation:
A list of trace indices that identify the respective traces in the
data attribute

props.name: baseframe
props.documentation:
The name of the frame into which this frame's properties are merged
before applying. This is used to unify properties and avoid needing
to specify the same values for the same properties in multiple frames.

props.name: data
props.documentation:
A list of traces this frame modifies. The format is identical to the
normal trace definition.

props.name: layout
props.documentation:
Layout properties which this frame modifies. The format is identical
to the normal layout definition.

props.name: duration
props.documentation: Sets the duration of the slider transition

props.name: easing
props.documentation: Sets the easing function of the slider transition

props.name: visible
props.documentation: Determines whether or not this step is included in the slider.

props.name: method
props.documentation:
Sets the Plotly method to be called when the slider value is changed.
If the `skip` method is used, the API slider will function as normal
but will perform no API calls and will not bind automatically to state
updates. This may be used to create a component interface and attach to
slider events manually via JavaScript.

props.name: args
props.documentation:
Sets the arguments values to be passed to the Plotly
method set in `method` on slide.

props.name: label
props.documentation: Sets the text label to appear on the slider

props.name: value
props.documentation:
Sets the value of the slider step, used to refer to the step programatically.
Defaults to the slider label if not provided.

props.name: execute
props.documentation:
When true, the API method is executed. When false, all other behaviors are the same
and command execution is skipped. This may be useful when hooking into, for example,
the `plotly_sliderchange` method and executing the API command manually without losing
the benefit of the slider automatically binding to the state of the plot through the
specification of `method` and `args`.

props.name: t
props.documentation: The amount of padding (in px) along the top of the component.

props.name: r
props.documentation: The amount of padding (in px) on the right side of the component.

props.name: b
props.documentation: The amount of padding (in px) along the bottom of the component.

props.name: l
props.documentation: The amount of padding (in px) on the left side of the component.

props.name: visible
props.documentation: Determines whether or not the slider is visible.

props.name: active
props.documentation:
Determines which button (by index starting from 0) is
considered active.

props.name: lenmode
props.documentation:
Determines whether this slider length
is set in units of plot *fraction* or in *pixels.
Use `len` to set the value.

props.name: len
props.documentation:
Sets the length of the slider
This measure excludes the padding of both ends.
That is, the slider's length is this length minus the
padding on both ends.

props.name: x
props.documentation: Sets the x position (in normalized coordinates) of the slider.

props.name: y
props.documentation: Sets the y position (in normalized coordinates) of the slider.

props.name: pad
props.documentation: Set the padding of the slider component along each side.

props.name: xanchor
props.documentation:
Sets the slider's horizontal position anchor.
This anchor binds the `x` position to the *left*, *center*
or *right* of the range selector.

props.name: yanchor
props.documentation:
Sets the slider's vertical position anchor
This anchor binds the `y` position to the *top*, *middle*
or *bottom* of the range selector.

props.name: font
props.documentation: Sets the font of the slider step labels.

props.name: activebgcolor
props.documentation:
Sets the background color of the slider grip
while dragging.

props.name: bgcolor
props.documentation: Sets the background color of the slider.

props.name: bordercolor
props.documentation: Sets the color of the border enclosing the slider.

props.name: borderwidth
props.documentation: Sets the width (in px) of the border enclosing the slider.

props.name: ticklen
props.documentation: Sets the length in pixels of step tick marks

props.name: tickcolor
props.documentation: Sets the color of the border enclosing the slider.

props.name: tickwidth
props.documentation: Sets the tick width (in px).

props.name: minorticklen
props.documentation: Sets the length in pixels of minor step tick marks
